Text: This week was busy for me as mentioned in the previous blog i was learning PHP, however the approach i took (reading PHP manual from start) while was really helpful in learning the ins and outs of the language proved to be really unproductive.
So i followed a video tutorial that Roro gave me and followed along to produce the code that i presented on friday.
It was basically a HTML form that had extra functionalities (Connect to MySQL database to produce Json and Autocomplete).
This meant that i technically didn't reach my goal of properly learning and understanding PHP (or atleast what i was implementing).
This was the case like how I learnt the two different ways of connecting to a MySQL database, either through MySQLI or through PDO.
I just know that PDO is good for security sakes as it allows for prepared statements, which prevents insertion of drop-tables.
But other than that i dont know the specifics.
I find it difficult to find documentation that starts on the topic from the beginning, and it results in tons of jargon or terminologies that i dont know.
I just end up testing the code and changing it slowly to suit my needs, which is relatively inefficient.
I was thinking that to prevent this from happening i was going to start taking notes on terminologies from documentation and tutorial videos, instead of vacantly following along with the coding.
This will help me with my long term goal of understanding the ins and outs of what im coding.
Another area of research i have been looking into was how websites function, and i was surprised to learn about what HTTP was actually.
Back to workflow wise, there has been some problems with the project.
Our group had a discussion that resulted in us changing the whole architecture of the project.
Swapping out MySQL out with MongoDB and having the PHP rely on an API call to MongoDB to retrieve information to display on leaflet.
The reasoning for this change was due to what we believe would make it easier for Kuku to integrate, atleast that is what thang believes.
I dont have enough understanding of the Kuku's system and generan knowledge to know if this was the right thing to do or not, but i think we still should have consulted with Kuku before pulling this.
Overall as well this could have been prevented if we properly went through the Agile methodolgy and created user stories.
